Five of the 17 SDGs showed a statistically significant linear response to ECSS. SDGs 6, 13 and 15 (goals related to water, climate, and ecosystem) had a significant positive relationship with ECSS. In contrast, SDGs 7 and 17 (goals related to energy and partnerships) had a negative relationship with ECSS (Fig. 4
                        ). In addition to the goals showing a significant linear relationship with ECSS, piecewise linear fitting was performed for the remaining targets. The results showed that SDGs 1, 4, 8 and 12 (goals related to poverty, education, economic growth, and consumption) had consistent thresholds for ECSS (Fig. 4). When the standardised carbon sequestration value is 0.11, the SDG index scores on both sides of the threshold showed different responses to ECSS. To the left of the ECSS threshold (i.e., ECSS <0.11), SDGs 1, 4, 8 and 12 showed a positive linear response to ECSS, while no significant linear relationship with ECSS existed when the standardised carbon sequestration value was larger than 0.11. We identified the actual ECSS value corresponding to the threshold and identified the regions besides the threshold (Fig. 5
                        ). The results showed that the area smaller than the threshold occupies most of the LP region, and the land use type is mainly grassland, cultivated land and construction land. The areas larger than the spatial threshold are concentrated on the east side of the LP region, where mountains and forests are widely distributed (Figs. 5 and 1).

The ECSS-SDGs relationships represented by our results partially coincide with the existing findings from different perspectives but unify them into the core issue of social-ecological sustainability. Previous studies have revealed the ecological mechanisms by which ECSS affects SDGs. For example, land use change can influence the achievement of multiple SDGs by regulating the supply of ecosystem services, especially SDGs 15, 11, 2 (ecosystems, cities, and agriculture) (Wang et al., 2022a). In addition, ecosystem restoration can support the realisation of SDGs 6, 13 and 15 by restoring the carbon sequestration capacity and coordinating the water-food-energy-ecosystem nexus (Yao et al., 2021). Our results show that ECSS is positively associated with SDGs 6, 13, and 15 (goals related to water, climate, and ecosystem). To the left of the ECSS threshold, SDGs 1, 4, 8, and 12 (goals related to poverty, education, economy and production) also showed a positive linear response to ECSS (Fig. 3). This is because ECSS can deliver benefits such as supporting agriculture, regulating water and air quality, and conserving habitat for biodiversity, with social benefits in livelihoods and ecological education (Chu et al., 2019; Li et al., 2019). To clarify the mechanism that ECSS contributes to the SDGs, we identified the goals and targets whose implementation is contributed by ECSS by sorting synergistic relationships among ecosystem services, the UN definition of each SDG, and literature evidence (Fig. 6
                     ; Table 1
                     ). ECSS's contribution to SDGs is achieved mainly by supporting multiple ecosystem services and maintaining planetary boundaries to implement the multidimensional goals included in SDGs. As a critical supporting service, ECSS sequesters the carbon that underpins the formation of soil and biomass (Zhang et al., 2022d), thus supporting the supply of other ecosystem services. ECSS supports, firstly, regulating services (e.g., climate regulation) through carbon fixation, as well as provisioning services (e.g., crop, fibre, wood, and medicine production) through biomass accumulation (Xia et al., 2022). The healthy ecosystems supported by ECSS also satisfy the cultural services that human beings obtain from nature, such as ecotourism, aesthetic appreciation and ecological education (Fig. 6). In addition, the area with high ECSS is usually the forested mountains in the southeast LP, where characterised with the low level of population density, transportation accessibility and urbanisation, leading to limited energy demand and international trade. Therefore, SDGs 7, 17 (energy and international partnership) are negatively correlated with ECSS (Fig. 4).
